I don&#39;t see any more difficulty with reading the half-w and wh letters 
than any of the others.  Again, I believe it is just practice that makes 
the difference, Moira.

Paige

Moira O&#39;Brien wrote:
&gt;
&gt; My personal opinion is that half Whitewheat and half Win make reading 
&gt; a lot more difficult.
&gt;
&gt; Moira
&gt;
&gt; On 10/12/2007, *Ted Larson Freeman* &lt; freeman@... 
&gt; &lt;mailto:freeman@...&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;     I think this is a solid, well-thought-out proposal. I&#39;ll suggest a
&gt;     name for it: &quot;QS-SAMPA Extended&quot;.
&gt;
&gt;     Until we have it implemented in a font, it&#39;s difficult to evaluate
&gt;     fully. In the meantime, I just have one question. Should there also be
&gt;     a half-Whitewheat, ie half-{W}?
&gt;
&gt;     Ted
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;     On Dec 10, 2007 3:11 AM, Benct Philip Jonsson &lt;bpj@...
&gt;     &lt;mailto:bpj@...&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt; # Corrected presentation of BPJ&#39;s proposal for
&gt;     &gt;  QS-SAMPA ligatures and half-letters
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  This one is with one exception, which is a correction,
&gt;     &gt;  a superset of the old one, and thus backwards
&gt;     &gt;  compatible, inserting some omissions -- notably half-t.
&gt;     &gt;  Please scrap the old version!
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  In the following QS letters and spellings are given
&gt;     &gt;  according to QS-SAMPA and enclosed in curly braces {lYk
&gt;     &gt;  DIs}, TO letters and spellings are given between
&gt;     &gt;  underscores _like this_. English phonemes are given in
&gt;     &gt;  slashes /laIk DIs/ in a SAMPA transcription modified
&gt;     &gt;  towards QS-SAMPA in that /y/ and /a/ are used rather
&gt;     &gt;  than /@/ and /{/. Phonetic transcription where
&gt;     &gt;  necessary is given in a similarly modified SAMPA in
&gt;     &gt;  square brackets [lyIk Dys].
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  My proposal is propose that *if* ligatures are to be
&gt;     &gt;  assigned to positions in QS-SAMPA this should better
&gt;     &gt;  not be done randomly, since the whole idea with QS-
&gt;     &gt;  SAMPA is to make QS-to-ASCII mappings less random.
&gt;     &gt;  Seeing that the letter positions in the ASCII range are
&gt;     &gt;  essentially used up by the basic QS letters, the most
&gt;     &gt;  consistent manner of catering for ligatures would be to
&gt;     &gt;  assign them to positions corresponding to accented
&gt;     &gt;  letters in the Latin-1 encoding, so that e.g. a vowel
&gt;     &gt;  with a particular accent mark stands for &#39;the
&gt;     &gt;  corresponding QS-SAMPA vowel with following {r}&#39; and
&gt;     &gt;  another accent mark for &#39;following {n}&#39;, a third for
&gt;     &gt;  &#39;preceding {j} or {I}&#39;.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  Personally I regard ligatures as &#39;typographic sugar&#39;
&gt;     &gt;  which should be regarded as by no means necessary or
&gt;     &gt;  required in ordinary typing. Looking in QM one sees
&gt;     &gt;  that those vowel+{r} combinations which happen to
&gt;     &gt;  correspond to lexical sets do *not* receive special
&gt;     &gt;  treatment compared to other combined letter sequences
&gt;     &gt;  in Read&#39;s QS handwriting. It seems to me the whole
&gt;     &gt;  business of ligatures in QS fonts is a carryover from
&gt;     &gt;  Shavian typography, but as some people like them, and
&gt;     &gt;  the vowel+{r} combination do correspond to single
&gt;     &gt;  sounds in non-rhotic accents they should be catered
&gt;     &gt;  for.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  ## The assignments
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  On p. 13 of QM Read gives what he intends as a full
&gt;     &gt;  list of vowel+r ligatures, which would give us
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  - {Er} = {�} (_merry_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {er} = {�} (_Mary_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {ar} = {�} (_marry_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Yr} = {�} (_mire_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Ar} = {�} (_mar_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Or} = {�} (_more_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {ur} = {�} (_moor_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {ir} = {�} (_mere_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {yr} = {�} (_murder_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Hr} = {�} (_sour_)
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  Correspondingly, with following {n}
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  - {En} = {�} (_pen_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {en} = {�} (_pain, pane_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {an} = {�} (_pan_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Yn} = {�} (_pine_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {An} = {�} (_Juan_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {On} = {�} (_pawn_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {on} = {�} (_bone_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {un} = {�} (_soon_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {in} = {�} (_wean_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {yn} = {�} (_pun_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Hn} = {�} (_town_)
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  Also, though less systematic, with preceding {j} or {I}
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  - {ju} = {�} (_cute_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {jur} = {�} (_cure_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {jyn} = {�} (_onion, million)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Iy} = {�} (_India_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Iyn} = {�} (_Indian_)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Iyr} = {�} (_windier_)
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  This leaves the capitals _P, L, M, B, C, F_ free to
&gt;     &gt;  assign to the half-letters and the {Vl} ligature:
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  - half-{p} = {P} (obvious, I hope)
&gt;     &gt;  - {Vl} = {L} (_ultra_)
&gt;     &gt;  - half-{w} = {M} (_M_ is upside-down _W_)
&gt;     &gt;  - half-{h} = {B} (_B_ is visually similar to _H_)
&gt;     &gt;  - half-{z} = {C} (_C_ is visually similar to the QS
&gt;     &gt;  half- {z}, and _c_ is sometimes
&gt;     &gt;  /s/, the voiceless counterpart to
&gt;     &gt;  /z/...)
&gt;     &gt;  - half-{T} = {F} (vague visual similarity between _F_
&gt;     &gt;  and _T_)
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  And in addition:
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  - half-{d} = {�} (_Ed_)
&gt;     &gt;  - alt-{D} = {�} (_other_ {Q�yr}, [�] is IPA for
&gt;     &gt;  SAMPA [D])
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  ## Notes on the assignments
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  The use of Hr = � and Hn = � is made necessary by the
&gt;     &gt;  fact that there is no accented H&#39;s! I hope the slash on
&gt;     &gt;  � and � will recall the crossbar on H.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  The letter _�_ (capital Y with dieresis) is not
&gt;     &gt;  included in the Latin-1 encoding, but it is included in
&gt;     &gt;  Windows-1252 encoding as character 159, and it can
&gt;     &gt;  hardly hurt to include an {Yn} ligature, if desired, as
&gt;     &gt;  character 159 in a QS-SAMPA font.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  With the acute accent essentially meaning &#39;preceding j
&gt;     &gt;  or I&#39; those assignments are admittedly not as
&gt;     &gt;  systematic. However {Iy} often corresponds to TO _ia_,
&gt;     &gt;  {Iyr} to TO _ier_ and {Iyn} to TO _ian_, which
&gt;     &gt;  hopefully can work as memory cues.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  Words like _cure_ are given with [jUy(r)] in the
&gt;     &gt;  pronunciation dictionaries. The CMUPD gives some items
&gt;     &gt;  with [ju(y)r], but they are all foreign names. It thus
&gt;     &gt;  seems reasonable to assume that [Uy(r)] corresponding
&gt;     &gt;  to _ur_ + vowel is phonemically /jur/ and should be
&gt;     &gt;  written {jur} in QS. I&#39;ve looked for examples in QM
&gt;     &gt;  without finding any, which isn&#39;t to say there aren&#39;t
&gt;     &gt;  any. NB that I mistyped {jur} as {jyr} in the first
&gt;     &gt;  version of this proposal.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  QM gives a ligature (or spelling) {jyn} corresponding
&gt;     &gt;  to the spelling _ion_ in the words _onion, minion,
&gt;     &gt;  pillion, million_. It seems defensible to map this
&gt;     &gt;  ligature {jyn} {�} by analogy with {Ian} = {�}.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  Perhaps {�} and {�} should be swapped so that alt-{D}
&gt;     &gt;  is {�} and half-{d} is {�}? All the other half-letters
&gt;     &gt;  are assigned to capitals however, and the IPA [�] =
&gt;     &gt;  SAMPA [D] *is* a rather solid memory cue, IMHO.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  These mappings to accented letters may be hard to type
&gt;     &gt;  with a standard British or American keyboard mapping
&gt;     &gt;  but they are infinitely more readable, and if someone
&gt;     &gt;  is in a situation where they are hard to type these
&gt;     &gt;  ligatures are after all simply dispensible. They are
&gt;     &gt;  easy to type with the US International keyboard layout,
&gt;     &gt;  which works reasonably well also with a British-Irish
&gt;     &gt;  physical keyboard. For information on these issues, see
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  &lt;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_and_American_keyboards
&gt;     &lt;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_and_American_keyboards&gt;&gt;.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  Last but not least: I am among those who find the
&gt;     &gt;  assignment of alt-{n} to _q_ bothersome, but I have
&gt;     &gt;  found a useable memory cue, in that both alt-{n} and
&gt;     &gt;  _q_ can be seen as circles with lines coming out at the
&gt;     &gt;  bottom.
&gt;     &gt;
&gt;     &gt;  /BP 8^)&gt;
