&gt;��SAMPA [D])&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��## Notes on the assignments&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��The use of Hr = � and Hn = � is made necessary by the
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��fact that there is no accented H&#39;s! I hope the slash on&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��� and � will recall the crossbar on H.&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��The letter _�_ (capital Y with dieresis) is not&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��included in the Latin-1 encoding, but it is included in
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��Windows-1252 encoding as character 159, and it can&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��hardly hurt to include an {Yn} ligature, if desired, as&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��character 159 in a QS-SAMPA font.&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��With the acute accent essentially meaning &#39;preceding j
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��or I&#39; those assignments are admittedly not as&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��systematic. However {Iy} often corresponds to TO _ia_,&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��{Iyr} to TO _ier_ and {Iyn} to TO _ian_, which&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��hopefully can work as memory cues.
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��Words like _cure_ are given with [jUy(r)] in the&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��pronunciation dictionaries. The CMUPD gives some items&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��with [ju(y)r], but they are all foreign names. It thus&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��seems reasonable to assume that [Uy(r)] corresponding
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��to _ur_ + vowel is phonemically /jur/ and should be&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��written {jur} in QS. I&#39;ve looked for examples in QM&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��without finding any, which isn&#39;t to say there aren&#39;t&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��any. NB that I mistyped {jur} as {jyr} in the first
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��version of this proposal.&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��QM gives a ligature (or spelling) {jyn} corresponding&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��to the spelling _ion_ in the words _onion, minion,&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��pillion, million_. It seems defensible to map this
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��ligature {jyn} {�} by analogy with {Ian} = {�}.&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��Perhaps {�} and {�} should be swapped so that alt-{D}&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��is {�} and half-{d} is {�}? All the other half-letters&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��are assigned to capitals however, and the IPA [�] =
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��SAMPA [D] *is* a rather solid memory cue, IMHO.&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��These mappings to accented letters may be hard to type&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��with a standard British or American keyboard mapping&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��but they are infinitely more readable, and if someone
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��is in a situation where they are hard to type these&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��ligatures are after all simply dispensible. They are&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��easy to type with the US International keyboard layout,&lt;br&gt;
&gt;��which works reasonably well also with a British-Irish
    &lt;br&gt;
&gt;��physical keyboard. For information on these issues, see&lt;br&gt;
